Use a 6.5 mm female jack, solder header pins on it, and plug it straight into the GPIO port. Simple is good here.
---
Use this wiring:
- P3 x1 x7 gnd (sleeve)
- P5 x1 dah (ring)
- P7 x1 dit (tip)
---
With this layout, ground x7 sits on P3. That is fine physically. The app should still use P3 as the default virtual ground.
---
The jack and cable should point outward, away from the screen and buttons. This is neater, sturdier, and less annoying than loose GPIO wires.
---
If your paddle uses a 3.5 mm plug, use a simple 3.5 mm to 6.5 mm adapter, just the usual audio sort.
---
You can also solder a suitable 3.5mm TRS jack - the GPIO can be reassigned in settings.
---
A straight key fits the same header:
- P3 x1 x7 gnd
- P7 x1 dit x6 SK
---
One adapter covers both cases:
- Paddle x1 P3 x6 P5 x6 P7
- Straight key x1 P3 x6 P7
---
If your wiring does not match this layout, change it from Settings x1 Keying x1 GPIO. You can move ditx6 SK, dah and the x7 ground pin in there.

Straight mode always uses the ditx6SK pin from that menu. This layout matches the fe~male jack to the GPIO header with the least swaps.
---
Regardless of layout, you always need a ground x7. P3 can be reassigned if that is more convenient, or you can use any Flipper ground pin. If your key has no ground con~tact, it will not work.
